 minimize energy losses. These properties are crucial in reducing power losses during electrical transmission. Glassy metals’ low magnetostriction and low core loss make them ideal for applications that require high efficiency and low noise operation, such as power transformers. Their use in this sector is expected to grow rapidly as electric grids modernize and the need for more efficient, compact, and durable transformer cores increases. The demand for reliable and energy-efficient power distribution systems worldwide is anticipated to further boost the adoption of glassy metals in the manufacturing of distribution transformers, as they help reduce energy wastage and increase the operational lifespan of these critical infrastructure components.</p><p>The use of glassy metals in distribution transformers also contributes to environmental sustainability by lowering the carbon footprint associated with energy losses in power systems. As global energy demand continues to rise, the need for highly efficient power distribution solutions becomes ever more critical. Glassy metals offer a promising solution, with their ability to reduce both energy consumption and maintenance costs over the long term. Additionally, the ability of these metals to be produced in a variety of forms, including thin ribbons, offers manufacturers more flexibility in designing transformers that meet specific operational requirements. The increasing trend toward the adoption of smart grids and the integration of renewable energy sources also presents further growth opportunities for glassy metals in the transformer market.</p><h4>Electric Machinery</h4><p>Electric machinery, particularly electric motors and generators, benefits from the high-performance attributes of glassy metals. These metals, with their excellent thermal stability, high strength, and magnetic properties, are well-suited for applications requiring high torque and efficiency. They are used in a variety of electric machinery types